  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">We derive general structure and rigidity theorems for submetries <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>M</mi><mo stretchy="false">→</mo><mi>X</mi></math> , where M is a complete Riemannian manifold with sectional curvature <math altimg="si2.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi mathvariant="normal">sec</mi><mspace width="0.2em"></mspace><mi>M</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>1</mn></math> . When applied to a non-trivial Riemannian submersion, it follows that <math altimg="si237.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi mathvariant="normal">diam</mi><mspace width="0.2em"></mspace><mi>X</mi><mo>≤</mo><mi>π</mi><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mn>2</mn></math> . In case of equality, there is a Riemannian submersion <math altimg="si25.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi mathvariant="double-struck">S</mi><mo stretchy="false">→</mo><mi>M</mi></math> from a unit sphere, and as a consequence, f is known up to metric congruence. A similar rigidity theorem also holds in the general context of Riemannian foliations.</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">Elsevier</subfield>
